[The term "infectious" refers to the ability of an organism to cause disease, while "contagious" refers to its ability to spread from person to person. Some organisms can be infectious without being contagious.

There were 7980 cases of pertussis in California reported statewide as of the 3rd week in September (2014), according to a news report posted recently by ProMED-mail (Pertussis - USA (19): (CA) increasing incidence, update 20140921.2792202). There are now 8278 cases statewide so far this year, compared to 1249 in the same period last year (2013), according to the news report above.

Pertussis has been on the increase throughout most of the world. This has been attributed in part to increased virulence and other genetic changes in the circulating clones of _Bordetella pertussis_, as well as waning or an ineffective immune response after vaccination. For a discussion of these problems, see moderator LL's comments in prior ProMED-mail posts on pertussis and moderator ML's comments in ProMED-mail post Pertussis - USA (04): (MT, CA) increased incidence 20140424.2426383.

In the US, DTaP and Tdap vaccines are used for pertussis immunization (http://www.cdc.gov/vaccines/vpd-vac/pertussis/default.htm#vacc). DTaP is given to children younger than 7 years of age, and Tdap is given to older children and adults. Children should get 5 doses of DTaP, one dose at each of the following ages: 2, 4, 6, and 15 through 18 months and 4 through 6 years. Adolescents 11 through 18 years of age (preferably at age 11-12 years) should receive a single dose of Tdap. One dose of Tdap is also recommended for adults 19 years of age and older who did not get Tdap as an adolescent. Expectant mothers should receive Tdap during each pregnancy, preferably at 27 through 36 weeks. Tdap should also be given to 7-10 year olds who are not fully immunized against pertussis. (Upper-case letters in these abbreviations denote full-strength doses of diphtheria (D) and tetanus (T) toxoids and pertussis (P) vaccine. Lower-case "d" and "p" denote reduced doses of diphtheria and pertussis used in the adolescent/adult-formulations. The "a" in DTaP and Tdap stands for "acellular," meaning that the pertussis component contains only a part of the pertussis organism.)

Antibiotic post exposure prophylaxis is used in all asymptomatic household contacts within 21 days of onset of cough in the index patient with pertussis and in persons within 21 days of exposure who are at high risk of developing severe pertussis and in persons who will have close contact with those at high risk of developing severe pertussis such as infants aged less than 12 months and women in their 3rd trimester of pregnancy, immunocompromised persons, and patients with moderate to severe medically treated asthma (http://www.cdc.gov/pertussis/outbreaks/PEP.html). - Mod.ML

The state of can be located on the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2864604,204. Shasta and Tehama counties in northern California can be seen on the map at http://geology.com/county-map/california-county-map.gif. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
